8) Now skim the Horn et al. paper, outline the question the authors were aiming to address and what strategies they used to address this question.\
\
The authors are trying to find a disease-segregating germline mutation in the promoter sequence of TERT that segregates concomitantly with melanoma. The hope is that determining germline mutations that cosegregate with disease in cancer-prone families can provide insights into the mechanizations of sporadically arising cancers. Horn et al. performed high throughput sequencing on members of a cancer-prone family, and revealed germ-line mutations that seemed to correlate with melanoma.\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\ri-576
\cf0 a) The authors start by evaluating a family pedigree for melanoma. Based on this pedigree, what type of inheritance likely explains it?\
\
It looks like an X-linked dominant trait with incomplete penetrance.\
\
b) An initial linkage analysis provided the authors with the chromosomal location of sequence changes associated with melanoma. The authors then performed high-throughput sequencing of this region. Why might the authors have done this instead of performing whole genome sequencing of these 8 individuals?\
\
High throughput sequencing is more accurate when sequencing smaller DNA regions. Additionally, if the authors had determined that a certain region of a certain chromosome was the likely location of sequence changes associated with melanoma, then mutations in that region are the ones that are going to affect the study, thusly sequencing the entire genome of these 8 individuals would\'92ve been unnecessary, time consuming and wasteful.\
\
c) How did the authors verify their genomic data?\
\
Genomic data that resulted from high-throughput sequencing was validated by Sanger sequencing, which is slower and more expensive, but less prone to errors.\
\
d) Three intronic variants were also detected as unique in affected versus unaffected individuals. Propose an explanation for how these intronic variants might lead to changes in 
